134","1056":"1056","1010":"1010","1120":"1120","1040":"1040","1050":"1050","about 1120":"omkring 1120","1070":"1070","Glenorchy, Argyll, Scotland":"Glenorchy, Argyll, Skotland","Scotland":"Skotland"},"nl":{"1040–1134":"1040–1134","1056–Male":"1056–Overleden","1050–Female":"1050–Overleden","1070–1120":"1070–1120","1010–1113":"1010–1113","–1104":"–1104","1104":"1104","before 1113":"vóór 1113","1113":"1113","about 1070":"circa 1070","1134":"1134","1056":"1056","1010":"1010","1120":"1120","1040":"1040","1050":"1050","about 1120":"circa 1120","1070":"1070","Glenorchy, Argyll, Scotland":"Glenorchy, Argyll, Schotland","Scotland":"Schotland"},"en":{"1040–1134":"1040–1134","1056–Male":"1056–Deceased","1050–Female":"1050–Deceased","1070–1120":"1070–1120","1010–1113":"1010–1113","–1104":"–1104","1104":"1104","before 1113":"before 1113","1113":"1113","about 1070":"about 1070","1134":"1134","1056":"1056","1010":"1010","1120":"1120","1040":"1040","1050":"1050","about 1120":"about 1120","1070":"1070","Glenorchy, Argyll, Scotland":"Glenorchy, Argyll, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"MacGregor","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish:  see  McGregor  ."],"variants":[{"name":"McGregor","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Griogair</b> or <b>Mac Greagair</b> ‘son of <i>Griogar</i>’, Gaelic form of the personal name   Gregory  . Compare   Grierson  .","History: The Scottish Highland clan McGregor claims descent from the king of Picts and Scots Kenneth MacAlpin (Cináed mac Ailpín; 810–858  AD ). The origins of the clan are unclear. In the 13th century it was established on lands on the shores of Loch Awe and already in conflict with its neighbors of Clan Campbell. By the 16th century the McGregors had retreated deep into Glen Strae and acquired the nickname ‘Children of the Mist’. In 1603 the clan was abolished by royal edict and many members of the clan changed their surname. A year later, the chief of Clan McGregor and eleven of his followers were hanged in Edinburgh. Despite the proscription, the clan survived and supported the king in the Scottish Civil War (1644–51). The exploits of the Jacobite leader Rob Roy McGregor (1671–1734) were romanticized in a novel by Sir Walter Scott. The proscription was eventually repealed in 1774."]}]},{"name":"Duncan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Donnchadh , also used among people without Scottish connections. This was the name of a 7th-century Scottish saint (abbot of Iona) and two medieval kings of Scotland. The final ‐<i>n</i> in the Anglicized form seems to be the result of confusion with the Gaelic word <i>ceann</i> ‘head’ in the Latinized form <i>Duncanus</i>.  Compare Irish  Donagh ."],"variants":[{"name":"Donnchadh","meanings":["Gaelic: compound of Old Celtic <i>donn</i> ‘brown’ + <i>chadh</i> ‘chief’ or ‘noble’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Duncan \"a Strailadh\" MacGregor was born in 1040 as the son of Sir John \"Eoin Mór\" MacGregor and An English Lady of Great Beauty. He had at least 1 son with Margaret Ross. He died in 1134, in Glenorchy, Argyll, Scotland, at the age of 94."},"et":{"1040–1134":"1040–1134","1056–Male":"1056–Surnud","1050–Female":"1050–Surnud","1070–1120":"1070–1120","1010–1113":"1010–1113","–1104":"–1104","1104":"1104","before 1113":"enne 1113","1113":"1113","about 1070":"umbes 1070","1134":"1134","1056":"1056","1010":"1010","1120":"1120","1040":"1040","1050":"1050","about 1120":"umbes 1120","1070":"1070","Glenorchy, Argyll, Scotland":"Glenorchy, Argyll, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland"},"fi":{"1040–1134":"1040–1134","1056–Male":"1056–Kuollut","1050–Female":"1050–Kuollut","1070–1120":"1070–1120","1010–1113":"1010–1113","–1104":"–1104","1104":"1104","before 1113":"ennen vuotta 1113","1113":"1113","about 1070":"noin 1070","1134":"1134","1056":"1056",